Deposition is the process by which dissolved materials are left behind when a liquid, such as water, evaporates or freezes. This can occur in various natural and industrial settings, such as the formation of salt crystals in the bottom of a lake or the creation of sedimentary rocks from the accumulation of sediments in a riverbed.
In the case of salt crystals forming in a lake, for example, as water evaporates, the dissolved salt is left behind in the remaining liquid, eventually forming a solid crystal. Similarly, in the case of sedimentary rocks, as sediments are deposited in a riverbed or other body of water, over time the sediments can become compacted and cemented together to form a solid rock.
